<HEADLINE>
FT  18 OCT 94 / UK Company News: Airtours stretches sea-legs in Pounds 35m
buy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BLACKWELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The detour by Airtours into the cruise market, launched in April with the
purchase of a Norwegian ship, has taken off faster than the group expected.
Yesterday the UK's second biggest holiday company paid Pounds 35m cash for a
second ship - almost six months before a single passenger embarks on an
Airtours cruise.
'We were surprised by the demand in the market place,' said Mr Hugh
Collinson, managing director, adding that potential customers had been
disappointed that more than 90 per cent of the cruises on the first ship had
already been sold.
'We were keen to get a second ship to take advantage of the pent up demand,'
he said.
The group's first boat, the Seawing, has room for 800 passengers, and sets
sail under the Airtours banner on March 25.
Its purchase for Pounds 16m was announced on April 28 at the same time as an
Pounds 82m rights issue and the acquisition of SAS Leisure for Pounds 74m.
The group said at the time that it had no immediate plans to invest in
further cruise ships.
The Nordic Prince, bought yesterday from Royal Caribbean Cruises, can take
more than 1,200 passengers. Airtours takes delivery at the beginning of next
year, but is leasing the ship back to Royal Caribbean until March 15.
Mr Collinson said the ship would then undergo a minor refit - mainly of
furnishings - and start operations for Airtours on May 6 from Palma in the
Mediterranean.
Airtours is using its existing marketing and reservation systems for its
cruise holidays, which can be combined with stays ashore.
Mr Collinson said summer prices for a flight and an inside cabin ranged from
Pounds 399 to Pounds 549 per person a week, which he claimed was Pounds 300
below competitors' prices.
April's rights issue price was 390p. Yesterday the shares edged ahead 3p to
455p.
</TEXT>
