FT  18 OCT 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Does it matter that Takin' Over The Asylum tacitly conveys the message that
most of the people in mental hospitals are rather charming eccentrics who
are kept inside largely because other people are intolerant of their quirky
little habits? Given the misery caused in some homes by the presence of
those with mental illnesses it seems unfortunate to say the least, yet last
week's episode was undeniably an entertaining piece of drama (9.00 BBC2).
This week's drama in the C4 series Alan Bleasdale Presents is Jim Morris's
play 'Blood On The Dole' which was first performed at the Liverpool
Playhouse in 1981: 'Four Merseyside teenagers struggle to forge their own
identities in an unsympathetic world blighted by unemployment and social
deprivation' (10.00). In the week when the first volume of Doris Lessing's
autobiography is published, she talks on Omnibus about her childhood in
Rhodesia and her move to England (BBC 1). We have heard a lot recently about
the assassination of Nicholas and Alexandra and their family in Russia in
1918 and we are not finished yet: Network First (10.40 ITV).
