<HEADLINE>
FT  18 OCT 94 / Blair at risk of revolt on defence
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Tony Blair is battling to head off a revolt by leftwing Labour
backbenchers in the Commons tonight in the first vote on defence policy
since he became party leader.
A group of leftwing MPs is expected to vote against the entire defence
estimates - the government's projected funding for the defence department -
defying Mr Blair's call for Labour MPs to abstain.
In an attempt to avoid a split Mr Blair last night tabled a wide-ranging
amendment condemning the government for imposing piecemeal cuts and failing
to hold a comprehensive review of defence policy.
His amendment also deplores the effect of the cuts on areas dependent on
defence contracts, and presses for more effective economic assistance for
hard-hit regions.
But the amendment fails to call for defence spending to be cut to the
average level of other western European countries, nor does it seek the
scrapping of the Trident missile system - as demanded by last week's Labour
conference.
This demand has again been backed by a group of prominent leftwing
backbenchers. They have tabled their own amendment to the government motion
seeking approval for the defence estimates.
If, in accordance with precedent, they are denied an opportunity to vote for
the amendment they will argue that voting against the entire estimate is the
only effective way of backing the decision taken by the conference.
Mr Malcolm Rifkind, the defence secretary, predicted yesterday that Mr Blair
would not be able to prevent another open split on defence policy.
</TEXT>
