<HEADLINE>
FT  18 OCT 94 / Ruling on council hearing due
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROB EVANS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Magill, Westminster City Council's district auditor, will announce
today whether he will disqualify himself from public hearings into
allegations of gerrymandering.
If he does, the hearings will not take place at all, he said yesterday. But
if he does not disqualify himself, they will start tomorrow morning.
The hearings were due to start yesterday but were delayed because lawyers
for Dame Shirley Porter, former leader of the council, wanted more time to
argue that Mr Magill should disqualify himself.
At yesterday's one-day hearing, Mr Andrew Arden QC, barrister for the group
of objectors which first lodged the allegations, urged that the hearings
start as soon as possible. He quoted from one of Dame Shirley's interviews
with Mr Magill in which she insisted that she was 'no Asil Nadir'.
Mr Anthony Scrivener QC, retained by Dame Shirley, said that Mr Magill
should step down because he had acted wrongly during his investigation. Mr
Scrivener said that Mr Magill used emotive words such as 'disgraceful',
'improper' and 'gerrymandering' when he announced his provisional findings
in January, and that he created the 'maximum amount of prejudice' by giving
a press conference.
After a four-year investigation Mr Magill, a senior partner at accountancy
firm Touche Ross, provisionally ruled that Dame Shirley and nine others
should repay Pounds 21.25m spent on selling council homes in marginal wards
to secure victory at the 1990 local elections.
</TEXT>
