<HEADLINE>
FT  18 OCT 94 / Endorsing a growing manufacturing reputation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
When the world's 18th-largest company opted to spend Pounds 450m on
extending its Cleveland factories, it gave a further vote of confidence in
the quality of British manufacturing.
The activities of Samsung, South Korea's biggest industrial group, range
from semiconductors, electronic watches and computers to shipbuilding, heavy
engineering, petrochemicals and medical equipment.
In the past month NEC, the Japanese electronics giant, Sharp, the Japanese
consumer electronics company and Philips of Holland have all announced
further investment in their UK manufacturing operations, chiefly in the
areas of semiconductors, television picture tubes and white goods.
In addition, Mr Phillip Samper, president of the computer division of Sun
Microsystems, the US workstation manufacturer, said the quality of portable
computers produced by Sun's Scottish plant was on a par with any other
manufacturing region.
Samsung is following this pattern. The company's expansion corresponds with
its stated corporate strategy which is to concentrate investment in
promising sectors of international industry rather than weakening its thrust
by over-diversification.
Mr Chan Bea, managing director of Samsung Electronics in the UK, said
manufacturing in Europe would also avoid regulatory problems with the
European Commission.
The company has been in the UK for 10 years. Its sales have grown 100 per
cent since 1989. It markets microwave ovens, television sets, portable audio
systems and midi systems as well as facsimile machines, computer monitors,
printers and typewriters. It already manufactures 700,000 television sets a
year on Teesside for export to Europe.
Mr Bea pointed out the proximity of Cleveland to Scotland's Silicon Valley
where there are a host of computer companies which could become customers
for Samsung's products.
Further afield the market is also buoyant. More than half the personal
computers sold throughout Europe are manufactured in the UK. About 10.3m
machines worth about Dollars 20bn (Pounds 12.6bn) were shipped to Europe in
1993. A recent Economist study suggested demand was set for double-digit
growth. It said: 'Business in the 1990s cannot compete without the
efficiency and technology provided by computers . . . the massive price
reductions of the past two years have played a vital part in promoting
continued growth in the sale of PCs.'
The picture for microwave ovens is less clear-cut. While the number of
first-time buyers is continually replenished, it is becoming a replacement
market. The UK is reckoned to be ahead of the rest of Europe, however.
Almost 90 per cent of European households have a washing machine, but only
about 33 per cent have microwave ovens.
Samsung's decision to move its European headquarters to the UK underscores
its decision to centralise European servicing operations at Telford.
The company believes that only eight key electronics brands will survive the
next decade. Its decision to expand in the UK and in Europe is a key element
in its strategy to be one of the survivors.
</TEXT>
