<HEADLINE>
FT  18 OCT 94 / Estate moves from carbon to silicon
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The choice of Wynyard Park for Samsung's electronics complex is not without
symbolic significance.
This agricultural land was part of the Londonderry family estate, a property
assembled by Victorian coal barons. This century the family fell on harder
times and its ancestral home, Wynyard Hall, and grounds were bought in 1987
by Sir John Hall, a self-made millionaire pitman's son.
Sir John, the developer of the Gateshead MetroCentre and chairman of
Newcastle United Football Club, saw Wynyard as a potential growth point for
the north-east's economic transformation.
In 1991 he said that development in the coming decade would provide up to
10,000 jobs. Yesterday he said that Wynyard, with Samsung now signed up,
would attract Pounds 1bn of investment.
Planning permission - unlikely to be a problem - is needed for Samsung's
400-acre site but Cameron Hall Developments, Sir John's company, already has
permission for business development on another 500 acres of the estate.
Intensive marketing of this site will now start. Executive housebuilding is
already under way elsewhere on the estate.
