<HEADLINE>
FT  18 OCT 94 / Career guidance for pupils attacked
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Too many sixth-formers attempt inappropriate academic courses after
receiving inadequate careers guidance, two government inspectorates say
today, John Authers writes.
The Further Education Funding Council for England and the Office for
Standards in Education, which monitors schools, said higher priority should
be given to work-related activities and opportunities for students to take
on 'adult responsibilities', rather than academic A-levels.
They also found that students wishing to move into further or higher
education received better support and help than those seeking work.
The inspectors recommended that colleges should give more attention to
action plans based on students' experience, and that performance indicators
should be used to evaluate careers guidance.
General National Vocational Qualifications (GNVQs) were piloted as an
alternative to A-levels last year, and can be used either for university
entrance or for moving straight to employment. The government hopes this
route will attract those who are unlikely to succeed at A-level. Students
arrive at university with an inadequate grasp of how to manage money, says a
survey by the National Westminster Bank and the University of Exeter. Most
do not count a student loan as a debt, and have unrealistic expectations of
their future earnings.
</TEXT>
