<HEADLINE>
FT  18 OCT 94 / London-led operation halts Dollars 10bn international fraud
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A Dollars 10bn (Pounds 6.3bn) bank fraud was prevented by an international
police operation led by the Metropolitan Fraud Squad.
Details of one of the biggest bank frauds yet attempted emerged yesterday on
the eve of the first National Fraud Forum, which brings together police,
City regulators and private-sector investigators to discuss how to improve
the country's record on fraud prevention and prosecutions.
The victim of the fraud attempt was Agricultural Bank of China, one of
China's big four banks. It involved the issue by the bank of Dollars 10bn in
letters of credit or bank certificates guaranteeing trade payments between
two companies. Letters of credit can be traded or used as collateral when
raising bank loans.
On April 1 last year the Hengshui Central branch of Agricultural Bank issued
200 of these certificates, in the name of United Asia (Group) Corporation, a
shell company based in North America, with payment due to Sherwood
Investments, of the Bahamas.
According to an official with knowledge of the case, the certificates were
genuine in that they were signed by two employees of the bank. However, they
may have been obtained by deception and their export out of China was also
probably illegal.
The official said that the perpetrators of the scheme were too greedy. 'If
there had been less money at stake, they might have got away with it,' he
said.
Most of the certificates were taken on a circuitous route through a series
of offshore centres to the City, where eventually they were presented to
Barclays Bank.
Investigators believe that the aim of presenting them to Barclays was to
obtain a receipt stating that the certificates had been lodged with the
bank. This receipt would then have been used to obtain substantial loans
from other banks.
However, Barclays had suspicions about the provenance of the certificates
and therefore contacted Agricultural Bank's head office and the Bank of
England.
Meanwhile, Chinese authorities had by July last year become aware of the
export of the letters of credit. Messages were sent to all international
banks via the Swift electronic funds transfer network, telling these banks
that the certificates should not be treated as legal tender.
The police in London and New York were alerted. In the next six months, they
recovered 193 of the certificates in London. Another six were found in the
US and West Indies. One was traced to a bank vault in Switzerland.
Mr Lei Ping Wu of Agricultural Bank's London office said that thanks to the
actions of the police, his bank had suffered no loss.
The individual who presented the certificates to Barclays has disappeared.
Several people have been imprisoned in China in connection with the case,
including two bank employees. No charges have been laid against anyone
outside China.
Fraud survey, Pages 33-35
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Agricultural Bank of China.
    United Asia (Group) Corp.
    Sherwood Investments.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
    CNZ  China, Asia.
    USZ  United States of America.
    BAZ  Bosnia-Hercegovina, East Europe.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9222 Legal Counsel and Prosecution.
</IN>
