<HEADLINE>
FT  18 OCT 94 / Minister resists roads budget cut
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Dr Brian Mawhinney, the Transport secretary, is resisting big cuts in next
year's road-building programme, in spite of his determination to promote
policies which are more sympathetic to environmental factors.
As Whitehall departments prepare to finalise their spending plans for next
year the Treasury is putting pressure on the Department of Transport to
reduce its annual Pounds 2bn roads budget, saying that Dr Mawhinney is in
the throes of a re-examination of policy.
But Dr Mawhinney is understood to have warned that it would be irresponsible
to carry out sweeping cuts in road building next year because of commitments
that the government has already made, and that any reductions in the
programme should be deferred.
According to transport department officials about Pounds 900m of the annual
budget is spent on the maintenance of existing roads, and this cannot be
reduced in any event. They say that much of the remaining Pounds 1.1bn has
already been earmarked for specific projects.
Instead, the department is saying that any cuts should come in the second
and third years of the Treasury's public spending projections. This would
allow the roads programme to gradually adapt to a shift in priorities away
from road building.
A senior official said: 'You simply couldn't cut more than Pounds lbn from
the programme in year one. That would produce the most absurd kind of cuts,
with motorways being half-finished and roads ending in the middle of
nowhere.'
At the Conservative party conference last week Dr Mawhinney talked of the
need to achieve 'a better balance between the economic benefits of motoring,
the public's right to choose to drive and what I have called social and
physical environmental protection'.
</TEXT>
