<HEADLINE>
FT  18 OCT 94 / Banks wary of auditing deregulation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER, Banking Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
New small businesses are likely to continue to be required by banks to have
their accounts audited in order to borrow money in spite of a government
initiative to reduce auditing burdens, the British Bankers' Association said
yesterday.
The association said banks would support the spirit of the government
deregulation initiative by 'not normally' requiring audited information for
small businesses exempted from such requirements under new legislation.
However, it said banks were likely to continue to ask for audited accounts
when a company had 'no regular or reliable management information,' or when
there was no account history against which to measure ability to repay debt.
Leaders of the association said this would probably include small business
start-ups. Banks will also retain the right to call for audited information
if terms and conditions of loans are not met, although this will be 'used
sparingly'.
The association insisted there was likely to be a significant change in the
behaviour of local managers as a result of guidance being sent out by all
large banks which will change policy to fit in with the government's
initiative.
Legislation has exempted companies with a turnover of less than Pounds
90,000 from having to have accounts audited, and those with a turnover of
between Pounds 90,000 and Pounds 350,000 can replace the audit with an
independent accountant's report.
Mr Paul Chisnall, an assistant director of the association, said banks had
shifted towards a greater appreciation of the benefits of deregulation but
he added that they would still have to 'look very closely' at small business
start-ups because of a lack of account history. Banks were likely to want
properly audited accounts in order to establish 'base figures' as they
started up.
Sir Nicholas Goodison, president, said that account audits were no longer
regarded by banks as an 'essential tool' in monitoring small businesses
because they reflected the past, and banks were more concerned with current
cashflow.
The Auditing Practices Board is expected later this week to publish
guidelines on reporting requirements for accountants who have to provide
independent reports as a substitute for audits in larger small businesses.
</TEXT>
