<HEADLINE>
FT  18 OCT 94 / Brent Walker jury retires
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The jury in the Brent Walker fraud trial retired yesterday to consider its
verdicts. After deliberating for the afternoon it failed to reach any
decisions and was sent away for a night in a hotel.
Mr George Walker, the former chairman and chief executive of the Brent
Walker Group, and Mr Wilfred Aquilina, its former finance director, are both
accused of fraudulently boosting the company's profits between 1984 and
1989.
Mr Walker denies four charges of theft involving Pounds 17m, two charges of
false accounting and one of conspiring to falsify the Brent Walker accounts
to overstate profits and assets.
Mr Aquilina denies one charge of theft involving Pounds 4.5m, three of false
accounting and one of conspiring to falsify the company's accounts.
The trial, in an annexe of the Old Bailey, started on June 2.
The prosecution alleges that the Brent Walker profits were illegally boosted
by Pounds 19.3m through bogus film rights transactions which in reality were
funded by Brent Walker money.
The transactions were then concealed by a complicated money laundering
operation involving offshore companies and trusts in the Bahamas, the Isle
of Man and Canada, it is alleged.
The prosecution said profit-boosting enabled a healthier picture of Brent
Walker to be presented to investors when the property and leisure group was
expanding in the mid-1980s.
</TEXT>
