<HEADLINE>
FT  18 OCT 94 / Texas cuts 900 jobs in management shake-up
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Texas Homecare, the UK's second biggest do-it-yourself stores chain, which
is owned by Ladbroke group, is cutting 900 jobs in its 240 stores as part of
a management restructuring.
The redundancies provide further evidence of the depressed state of the DIY
market - one of the fastest-growing sectors of retailing in the 1980s -
which Ladbroke said yesterday remained 'highly competitive'.
Sales growth is slow, with little sign of stimulus from a recovery in the
housing market. Many analysts believe that with more than 1,000 DIY
superstores in operation there is too much capacity in the market.
About half the planned job losses come from reducing the average number of
managers and assistant managers in stores from seven to five, with some
administrative functions being taken over by computer systems. Remaining
assistant managers are being retrained and will spend more of their time on
the shopfloor to improve service.
The other losses result from closure of Texas Pantries snack bars in 170
stores.
Ladbroke said research by Mr John Coleman, the Texas chief executive
recruited from fashion chain Dorothy Perkins last year, showed that the
snack bars did not fit the chain's image and were being under-used.
The group said there was little scope for redeployment of staff, although
generous redundancy terms were being offered.
Restructuring costs of about Pounds 2m will be charged to this year's profit
and loss account, but Ladbroke said resulting cost savings would be
'considerable'.
The recent half-year results of the top three chains reflect the squeeze.
Texas reported a fall in profits from Pounds 16.6m to Pounds 2m.
B&amp;Q, the market-leader owned by Kingfisher, saw interim profits increase
slightly from Pounds 41.6m to Pounds 44.5m, but the number three, Do It All,
a joint venture between Boots and WH Smith which is selling 100 of its 240
stores, could only reduce its loss from Pounds 14.3m to Pounds 10.5m.
Mr Coleman is attempting to improve Texas's performance by cutting the
number of suppliers from 400 to 200, and renegotiating terms.
He is also refitting 50 stores and introducing more 'heavy' items such as
bricks, cement and timber - often in space vacated by the snack bars - to
cater properly for the 'high-spending DIY enthusiast'.
Ladbroke, which has no other retail interests apart from Texas, says it has
no plans to sell the chain, but analysts believe it might be prepared to if
its performance could be improved sufficiently to attract buyers.
</TEXT>
