FT  18 OCT 94 / No formal Kuwait recognition
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARK NICHOLSON and MICHAEL LITTLEJOHNS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BAGHDAD, NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Iraq's parliament ended a special session yesterday by backing President
Saddam Hussein's handling of thorny relations with the United Nations, but
did not reveal if it had approved the recognition of Kuwait's borders and
the Gulf state's sovereignty - a fundamental Security Council precondition
for any moves towards the easing of sanctions.
The hastily called meeting had been widely expected to meet the terms
required by this weekend's Security Council resolution, calling on Iraq to
make the recognition through 'full and formal constitutional procedures'.
But no announcement came at the end of the meeting. At the UN in New York,
Mr Andrei Kozyrev, the Russian foreign minister, reported formally on his
Baghdad talks and reiterated Moscow's view members should consider lifting
the oil embargo in about six months if Iraq showed honest co-operation and
followed through with recognition of Kuwait's borders. Ms Madeleine
Albright, the US delegate, responded that the crisis created by the recent
Iraqi troop deployments was still not over. As for promises made to Mr
Kozyrev, the US placed no more value on these than on previous Iraqi
pledges. The council should categorically reject any idea of rewarding Iraq
for 'partial compliance with some of its obligations', she said, citing a
list of other requirements under UN resolutions.
