<HEADLINE>
FT  18 OCT 94 / Interest rate controls lifted
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GERARD BAKER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Bank interest rates in Japan were yesterday freed from final government
controls, as the finance ministry completed a series of deregulatory
measures begun in 1985. Interest rates on ordinary and savings deposits rose
slightly above peviously fixed levels, in line with the general upward drift
in market interest rates. Rates on ordinary bank deposits, which were a
uniform 0.22 per cent a year, increased to between 0.27 per cent and 0.3 per
cent at the country's main commercial banks. Rates on time savings deposits
rose by between 0.05 and 0.1 percentage points. Until 1985, virtually all
Japanese interest rates were fixed by the government, as it sought to keep
borrowing and lending rates low to finance post-war economic reconstruction.
But, under pressure from foreign governments and financial institutions, the
finance ministry allowed a limited deregulation of interest rates that year.
The deregulation will put further competitive pressure on banks, already
weakened by bad debts.
</TEXT>
