FT  18 OCT 94 / Gaza witnesses second day of riots
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JULIAN OZANNE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Palestinian students rioted in Gaza for a second day in a row yesterday,
following an upsurge in militant feeling after the killing of three Islamic
kidnappers in an Israeli raid last week and an internal Palestinian
crackdown on the fundamentalist organisation, Julian Ozanne reports.
The students, supporters of the Hamas Islamic group responsible for the
kidnapping and killing of an Israeli soldier, stoned a joint patrol of
Israeli and Palestinian police and overran an Israeli military checkpoint.
The continuing riots reveal the bitter divide which has emerged between Mr
Yassir Arafat's Palestine Liberation Organisation and Hamas since the
kidnapping crisis.
In an effort to calm the tension, Mr Arafat yesterday began releasing some
of the 300 Hamas activists he arrested last week and detained a PLO general
who ordered his troops to fire in the air during a Hamas demonstration at
the Gaza central prison on Saturday.
Mr Arafat's advisers have warned the PLO leader against giving in to Israeli
and western pressure to deal a decisive blow to Hamas, which could risk
civil war.
But relations between the PLO and Hamas, which opposes peace with Israel and
is bent on the destruction of the Jewish state, have reached an all-time low
and have left deep uncertainty about political stability in the Gaza Strip.
