<HEADLINE>
FT  18 OCT 94 / Lisbon looks for revenue rise
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER WISE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LISBON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Portugal's centre-right government yesterday presented to parliament a
moderately restrictive budget for 1995 that allows room for a high level of
European Union-financed investment in the approach to a general election
next October. Mr Eduardo Catroga, finance minister, said the budget deficit
would be cut to 5.8 per cent of gross domestic product from an estimated 6.3
per cent this year. This would be achieved through increased revenue rather
than by spending cuts, consolidating a downward trend after a large overrun
in 1993. Overall revenue next year was forecast to grow by 7 per cent
compared with 1994, to Es3,649.2bn (Pounds 14.7bn). The central value added
tax rate would be raised from 16 to 17 per cent, but Mr Catroga said direct
tax would not rise as a percentage of GDP. Public spending would rise 5.2
per cent, above forecast 1995 inflation of 3.5-4.5 per cent, to Es4,380.8bn.
</TEXT>
