<HEADLINE>
FT  18 OCT 94 / Competitive role for mobile phones
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mobile phone companies could play a critical role in boosting competition
across Europe's telecommunications industry as existing monopolies are
abolished, the European Commission believes.
Mr Leo Koolen, a senior Commission official, told a Financial Times
conference on mobile communications in London yesterday that mobile phone
operators would be well placed to com-pete with existing 'fixed-wire'
operators when the monopoly of national phone companies over basic phone
calls is abolished in 1998.
Commission projections show the number of mobile telephone subscribers in
Europe rising from about 12m - three times the level of three years ago - to
at least 40m by 2000 and 80m by 2010.
'We believe that the mobile and personal communications sector has the
potential to grow to a size equivalent to the present fixed-wire sector in
just one and a half decades,' said Mr Koolen.
The mobile communications sector has been opened to competition across the
European Union. Within the past two years industrial groups such as
Mannesmann in Germany and Bouygues in France, with no previous telecoms
business, have taken significant stakes in the cellular market, in
competition with established operators Deutsche Telekom and France Telecom
and
As a first stage in opening up fixed-wire telecoms networks to competition,
the Commission wants mobile operators to be allowed to build their own fixed
links as a means of reducing their reliance on existing monopoly networks.
This will be covered by a green paper on telecoms infrastructure
liberalisation, to be published early next year.
However, Mr Koolen said the Commission also envisaged mobile operators
competing head-on with fixed-wire companies once the latter's monopoly over
basic voice telephony is abolished in 1998.
In the UK - the EU's most open telecoms market - Mercury Communications, the
main competitor to the former monopoly British Telecommunications, is a
significant operator in both the mobile and fixed-wire markets.
The Commission believes a similar pattern could develop across the EU as
liberalisation advances.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
    XGZ  Europe.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9631 Regulation, Administration of Utilities.
    P4812 Radiotelephone Communications.
</IN>
