<HEADLINE>
FT  17 OCT 94 / World Bond Markets: Frankfurt
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW FISHER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Yesterday's German election, in which Chancellor Helmut Kohl was last night
heading for a narrow majority, took place against the background of an
economic recovery that looks increasingly solid and an inflation rate
expected to ease from the current 3 per cent this year.
It is these economic fundamentals and the gradual slowdown of money supply
growth which will determine the progress of the bond market, along with
events in the US, once the vote's outcome has been digested.
The bond and stock markets rose last week, with 10-year bund yields easing
towards 7.50 per cent, on the growing assumption that Mr Kohl's coalition
government would be re-elected.
Earlier, however, investors were not so certain and the markets softened.
The prospect of a Kohl victory and the continuation
of deficit-reducing fiscal
policies injected a new confidence into the market. Thus said Ms Alison
Cottrell, international economist at Kidder, Peabody Securities: 'If bond
markets had votes, Mr Kohl - rightly or wrongly - would romp home.'
Even if he was not voted in again, she recommended investors to move up the
yield curve, not jump off. The Bundesbank would see to it that any fiscal
laxity in Bonn was met with stern monetary policies.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>DEZ  Germany, EC.
